concept_explanation.extends_and_inheritance:
The `extends` keyword creates the parent-child relationship:

```java
public class Animal {
    protected String name;   // protected — accessible by subclasses
    protected int age;

    public Animal(String name, int age) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
    }

    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " makes a sound");
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return name + " (age " + age + ")";
    }
}

public class Dog extends Animal {
    private String breed;   // Dog-specific field

    public Dog(String name, int age, String breed) {
        super(name, age);   // call Animal's constructor
        this.breed = breed;
    }

    public void fetch() {  // Dog-specific method
        System.out.println(name + " fetches the ball!");
    }

    public String getBreed() { return breed; }
}

Dog d = new Dog("Rex", 3, "Labrador");
System.out.println(d);    // calls Animal's toString: "Rex (age 3)"
d.makeSound();             // inherited from Animal
d.fetch();                 // Dog's own method
```

concept_explanation.super_keyword:
**`super`** refers to the PARENT class — analogous to how `this` refers to the current object.

**Two main uses**:

**1. Call parent constructor**: `super(args...)` — MUST be the first line of the subclass constructor.

```java
class Dog extends Animal {
    private String breed;

    public Dog(String name, int age, String breed) {
        super(name, age);  // calls Animal(String, int) — FIRST LINE
        this.breed = breed;
    }
}
```

Why must it be first? The parent needs to be initialized before the child adds its own state.

If you don't call `super(...)`, Java calls the no-arg parent constructor automatically. If the parent doesn't HAVE a no-arg constructor, you get a compilation error.

**2. Call overridden parent method**: `super.methodName()` — calls the parent's version.

```java
class Animal {
    public String toString() {
        return name + " (age " + age + ")";
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return super.toString() + " [" + breed + "]";  // reuses parent's toString
    }
}
// Dog.toString() returns: "Rex (age 3) [Labrador]"
```

Using `super.method()` lets you EXTEND parent behavior instead of completely replacing it.

concept_explanation.method_overriding:
**Overriding**: subclass provides a NEW implementation of a parent method.

```java
class Animal {
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " makes a sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Woof!");
    }
}

class Cat extends Animal {
    @Override
    public void makeSound() {
        System.out.println(name + " says: Meow!");
    }
}
```

Each subclass provides its own `makeSound`. The `@Override` annotation confirms it truly overrides (catches typos in method name).

**Overriding rules**:
- Same method name
- Same parameter list
- Return type: same OR a subtype (covariant return)
- Access: same or MORE permissive (can't make more restrictive)
- Can't override `final` methods

**Overriding vs Overloading** (common confusion):
- **Overriding**: same name, SAME parameters, different class (runtime behavior)
- **Overloading**: same name, DIFFERENT parameters, same class (compile-time selection)

concept_explanation.final_class_final_method:
**`final` class**: cannot be extended. No subclasses allowed.

```java
public final class String { ... }  // can't extend String
public final class Integer { ... } // can't extend Integer
```

String and Integer are final — Java's designers didn't want custom subclasses messing with their behavior.

**`final` method**: cannot be overridden in subclasses.

```java
class BankAccount {
    protected double balance;

    public final void audit() {  // cannot be overridden
        System.out.println("Auditing account: balance = " + balance);
    }
}

class SavingsAccount extends BankAccount {
    // CANNOT override audit() — it's final in BankAccount
}
```

Used when: you have critical logic that MUST NOT be altered by subclasses (security, financial calculations). The `final` method is a declaration: 'This implementation is correct. Trust it. Don't change it.'

concept_explanation.what_is_not_inherited:
Subclasses do NOT inherit:
- `private` fields and methods (visible only in the class they're defined)
- Constructors (you must call parent constructor via `super()`)

**Private field gotcha**:
```java
class Animal {
    private String name;  // private — not inherited

    public String getName() { return name; }  // PUBLIC getter IS inherited
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void test() {
        System.out.println(name);      // COMPILE ERROR — can't access
        System.out.println(getName()); // OK — inherited public getter
    }
}
```

Private fields are hidden. Subclasses must use the parent's public/protected getters. This is why proper encapsulation (from Topic 4.3) matters so much — it determines what subclasses can access.

**Constructor gotcha**:
```java
class Animal {
    Animal(String name) { ... }  // constructor, NOT inherited
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    Dog(String name, String breed) {
        super(name);  // MUST explicitly call Animal's constructor
        ...
    }
}
```

step_by_step_solution.details:
```java
class Employee {
    private static int nextId = 1;

    private final int employeeId;
    private String name;
    private double salary;

    public Employee(String name, double salary) {
        if (name == null || name.isBlank()) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Name required");
        if (salary < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Salary cannot be negative");
        this.employeeId = nextId++;
        this.name = name;
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    public int getEmployeeId() { return employeeId; }
    public String getName() { return name; }
    public double getSalary() { return salary; }

    public void giveRaise(double percent) {
        salary *= (1 + percent / 100);
    }

    public String getDescription() {
        return "Employee[#" + employeeId + " " + name + ", salary=₹" + salary + "]";
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return getDescription();
    }
}
```

Notice ALL fields are `private` — practicing what the topic preaches. Subclasses will read `name` through the public `getName()` getter, not by touching the field directly. `salary` modifications must go through `giveRaise()` (controlled access).

```java
class Manager extends Employee {
    private int teamSize;

    public Manager(String name, double salary, int teamSize) {
        super(name, salary);  // call Employee constructor — MUST be first
        if (teamSize < 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException("Team size cannot be negative");
        this.teamSize = teamSize;
    }

    public int getTeamSize() { return teamSize; }

    @Override
    public String getDescription() {
        return super.getDescription() + " | Manager of " + teamSize + " people";
    }
}
```

Three key moves:
1. `super(name, salary)` — first line, delegates to Employee's constructor
2. Add `teamSize` field (Manager-specific)
3. Override `getDescription()` — EXTEND parent's description with team info using `super.getDescription()`

```java
class Developer extends Employee {
    private String primaryLanguage;

    public Developer(String name, double salary, String primaryLanguage) {
        super(name, salary);  // Employee constructor
        this.primaryLanguage = primaryLanguage;
    }

    public String getPrimaryLanguage() { return primaryLanguage; }

    @Override
    public String getDescription() {
        return super.getDescription() + " | Developer (" + primaryLanguage + ")";
    }
}
```

Same pattern: `super(...)` first, add own field, override `getDescription()` to extend parent's version.

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    // Create specific types
    Manager aisha = new Manager("Aisha", 120000, 8);
    Developer raj = new Developer("Raj", 85000, "Java");
    Developer priya = new Developer("Priya", 92000, "Python");

    // Can store all in Employee[]
    Employee[] team = {aisha, raj, priya};

    System.out.println("=== Team Directory ===");
    for (Employee e : team) {
        System.out.println(e.getDescription());
    }

    // Give everyone a 10% raise
    System.out.println("\n=== After 10% Raise ===");
    for (Employee e : team) {
        e.giveRaise(10);  // works on all — giveRaise is in Employee
        System.out.println(e.getName() + " now earns ₹" + e.getSalary());
    }
}
```

This is the payoff: an `Employee[]` holds Managers, Developers — any subclass. The loop calls `getDescription()` and each object uses ITS OWN version. This is **polymorphism** — the topic we'll deepen in Topic 5.2.

